    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n**1\\.** As pointed out by a Matrix user, `nvim_create_autocmd` skips empty `pattern`s, and falls back to the default of `*` if all patterns are empty.\n\nThis works well for `nil`, but means:\n - `nil` acts like `{\"*\"}` (good) \n - `{}` acts like `{\"*\"}` (ew)\n - `\"\"` acts like `{\"*\"}` (ew)\n - `{\"\", \"\"}` acts like `{\"*\"}` (ew)\n -  `{\"\", \"foo\", \"\", \"bar\"}` acts like `{\"foo\", \"bar\"}` (oof; empty patterns are silently ignored)\n\n---\n\n**2\\.** Empty comma-delimited patterns in `:autocmd` are parsed strangely. Also applies when using `nvim_create_autocmd` with a string `pattern` with commas.\n\nExample:\n```vim\n:autocmd User foo,bar,,baz,bazzier,,,bazziest \"\n:autocmd User\n```\nOutput:\n```\n--- Autocommands ---\nUser\n    foo       \"\n    bar       \"\n    ,ba       \"\n    z         \"\n    bazzier   \"\n    ,,bazzie  \"\n    st        \"\n```\n\nVim parses these fine: (but silently skips the empty patterns)\n```\n--- Autocommands ---\nUser\n    foo       \"\n    bar       \"\n    baz       \"\n    bazzier   \"\n    bazziest  \"\n```\n\nHaven't looked into how long that's been broken for; maybe since `nvim_create_autocmd` was introduced? (it did have to refactor a lot of autocmd stuff...)\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `nvim_create_autocmd` with an empty table or string `pattern`, or a table `pattern` containing empty strings.\n2. Defining autocommands via `:autocmd` while using empty comma-delimited patterns.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n1. Empty `pattern`s should probably raise an error. `nil` `pattern`s should continue to fall back to `*`.\n2. Parse empty comma-delimited patterns correctly, like Vim. (maybe ignore them too for compatibility)\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-1850+g99e8b61376\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, 9.1.1997\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nFedora 43\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nghostty 1.2.3, tmux 3.5a\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nSource",
